Plotting

One key tool in analytics is data visualization. Indeed, a picture speaks a thousand words. We will first investigate some basic plots that base R (i.e.no packages) offers, then transition into using a powerful package called ggplot2

Data

We will be using a dataset called mpg, which is self-loaded by importing ggplot (make sure you call library(ggplot2) first). You can find more about the dataset here.

Some basic plots

hist

If we want to see the distribution of city miles per gallon for all models(cty), we can make a histogram. To call up a column from a dataframe, we use the $ symbol. Note that its sufficient to only specify the column graphed, but we can add in (optional) additional arguments to improve our graph.

# hist(mpg$cty) this is sufficient
hist(mpg$cty, main = 'Histogram of cty', xlab = 'miles per gallon')

In general, some main embellishments that work in base R:

  • main: the title of the graph
  • ylab/xlab: the y and x labels
  • ylim/xlim: the limits of the y/x axis. Note that they take in a vector with two numbers that signify the lower/upper limits. e.g.xlim = c(0, 100)

pie

We may want to understand the distribution of car types using a pie chart. We first need to count how many instances of each type of car is present. Theres a funciton in dplyr called count that does this.

car_types = mpg %>% count(class)
print(car_types)
## # A tibble: 7 x 2
##   class          n
##   <chr>      <int>
## 1 2seater        5
## 2 compact       47
## 3 midsize       41
## 4 minivan       11
## 5 pickup        33
## 6 subcompact    35
## 7 suv           62

Note that under the hood, this is the real function being run: mpg %>% group_by(class) %>% summarize(counts = n()) i.e.first group by class, and then do a count for each class, with n() being the function for count

Then we can call up a pie chart. The format here is pie(counts of the car types, (optional)labels of car types, (optional)radius of the chart)

pie(car_types$n, labels = car_types$class, radius = 1)

While base R does offer a variety of different types of plots (i.e.line, hist, scatter, etc), the amount of customization is limited. Furthermore, the syntax/pre-treatment required can get complicated especially when we try to have multiple components in the same graph (e.g.line charts with multiple lines). This prompts us to seek for a new way of plotting.

ggplot

What is ggplot?

In short, its a plotting library that allows for more beautiful and complex plots than the default options in R. Below are some of the fundamental components of a ggplot:

  • ggplot() creates an empty coordinate graph. The idea is for you to add layers of graphs.
  • Every function in ggplot2 takes a mapping argument, which is always paired with aes(x,y).
  • Aesthetic = visual property of objects in the plot; color, alpha, size, shape
  • Facets = subplots
  • Geom = the geometrical object that a plot uses to represent data (e.g.bar, line)

Code template:

ggplot(data = <DATA>) +  
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(  
     mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>),  
     stat = <STAT>,  
     position = <POSITION>  
  ) +  
  <COORDINATE_FUNCTION> +  
  <FACET_FUNCTION>

Aesthetics

# Here, we map the aesthetic "color" to the variable "class"
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=class))

# Outside of aes(), the arguments are applied to the entire plot
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy), 
             color='blue', alpha=0.2, size=3, shape=18)

Facets

facet_wrap() lets you subplot by a single variable.
To subplot by multiple variables, use facet_grid().

# face_wrap()
ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow=2)

# facet_grid()
ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

Geoms

Some aesthetics work only with certain geoms (e.g.shape would not make sense with lines.)
Global mapping is applied to each layer, and local maping is added on for that layer only.

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=drv)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(linetype=drv)) +
  geom_point()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
